            <title><![CDATA[Epic, A Company That Makes Billions Of Dollars, Is Jacking Up The Price Of Fortnite's V-Bucks 'To Help Pay The Bills']]></title>
            <link>https://aftermath.site/epic-v-bucks-price-increase-fortnite/</link>
            <guid>1460434</guid>
            <content:encoded><![CDATA[<div id="readability-page-1" class="page"><div id="main">
      
    

<div data-post-date-group="" data-post-info="">
      <p><span>Published:</span>
        <time datetime="2026-03-11T08:01:00">March 11, 2026, 8:01 pm</time>
      </p>
        <p><i role="presentation">
  <svg xmlns="http://www.w3.org/2000/svg" width="24" height="24" viewBox="0 0 24 24" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="2" stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round"><path stroke="none" d="M0 0h24v24H0z" fill="none"></path><path d="M6 6v6a3 3 0 0 0 3 3h10l-4 -4m0 8l4 -4"></path></svg>
</i>          <span>Last updated:</span>
          <time datetime="2026-03-11T08:03:04">March 11, 2026, 8:03 pm</time>
        </p>
    </div>
    <article>
      <p>In a short statement that could only have been published by<a href="https://aftermath.site/tim-sweeney-x-ai-csam-epic-games-fortnite/"> <u>a company run by Tim Sweeney</u></a>, Epic Games have bluntly announced that the price of V-Bucks, the virtual currency used to buy stuff in <em>Fortnite</em>, is going up.</p><p>The one line explanation for the increase<a href="https://www.fortnite.com/news/fortnite-v-bucks-price-increase?ref=aftermath.site"> <u>reads</u></a>:</p><blockquote>The cost of running Fortnite has gone up a lot and we’re raising prices to help pay the bills.</blockquote><p>Three things to consider here!</p><p>1) In most places that <em>Fortnite </em>is played in, the average worker and consumer has suffered for years through a succession of inflationary crises,<a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/2021%E2%80%932023_inflation_surge?ref=aftermath.site"> <u>first during the pandemic</u></a>, and more lately through<a href="https://apnews.com/article/inflation-gas-oil-trump-7303e4593d62c2dee899489571cb0548?ref=aftermath.site"> <u>psychotic government policy affecting global markets</u></a>. So yes, the cost of <em>everything </em>has gone up.</p><p>2) That burden is one being borne by workers and consumers. As the ones actually having to pay more for pretty much <em>everything</em>, while<a href="https://www.epi.org/productivity-pay-gap/?ref=aftermath.site"> <u>wage growth remains stagnant</u></a>, we understand that. Meanwhile Epic Games, the company that developed <em>Fortnite </em>and runs <em>Fortnite</em>, makes <em>billions </em>of dollars every year. By raising the price of V-Bucks to compensate for increased running costs, which a company making billions of dollars every year can easily absorb, that company is simply transferring the burden of inflation from their own books onto those of the already-suffering consumers.</p><p>3) Epic Games can get straight in the bin.</p><figure><blockquote data-bluesky-uri="at://did:plc:kp7occhnusry6di2i2hv2pfx/app.bsky.feed.post/3mgsnpb73yh2g" data-bluesky-cid="bafyreiag7pwvv24kf7zyrwj6cwengjscoi2wucgtro7lxrndn3xwccjhmq"><p lang="en">I tried asking Epic for more information on their "the cost of running Fortnite has gone up a lot and we’re raising prices to help pay the bills” statement—a statement that feels exceptionally out of touch in this economy—and was told the company would not be elaborating.</p>— <a href="https://bsky.app/profile/did:plc:kp7occhnusry6di2i2hv2pfx?ref_src=embed&amp;ref=aftermath.site">Patrick Klepek (@patrickklepek.bsky.social)</a> <a href="https://bsky.app/profile/did:plc:kp7occhnusry6di2i2hv2pfx/post/3mgsnpb73yh2g?ref_src=embed&amp;ref=aftermath.site">2026-03-11T19:48:10.883Z</a></blockquote></figure>
    </article>

        

      

          

